library(ggplot2)
head(mpg)

ggplot() creates a cooridnate systhem that you can add layers on.

rr ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

Ex 3.2.4

rr dim(mpg)

[1] 234  11

rr mpg %>% ggplot(aes(x = class, y = drv)) + geom_point()

3.3

rr mpg %>% ggplot(aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) + geom_point(aes(col = class))

codes from book

rr ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, col = class))

Notes: to map an aesthetic to a variable, associate the name of the aesthetic to the name of the variable inside aes(). ggplot2 will automatically assign a unique level of aesthetic (color here) to each unique value of the variable, a process known as scaling.

Mapping an unordered varialbe (class) to an ordered aesthetic (size) is not a good idea, thus we got a warning for doing this.

rr mpg %>% ggplot(aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + geom_point(aes (size = class))

aes alpha controls the transparency aes shape controls the shape

mpg %>% ggplot() + geom_point(aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = class))

If you want to manually set the aesthetic properties that do not convey information from the data set, it goes outside of aes()

rr mpg %>% ggplot() + geom_point(aes(x = displ, y = hwy), col = )

other manual aesthetic settings include * color * size (mm) * the shape of points
